segments.text: I am John M. Lawrence, Jr.
I was born here in Brown in October 1899 in a house located at West 16th and Parker Street.
In 1907, my parents moved to
East 26th and Texas Avenue, where they erected a two-story frame colonial home.
I lived there until maturity.
I have lived in Brown all of my life and have been engaged in various activities.
My first occupation was shipping clerk for
a wholesale grocery company.
Then I went into a combination automobile dealership garage and service station in 1923, which I operated until 1931.
At that time, I became book agent for a minor heart company and also worked part-time as an appraiser or inspector for the Regional Agricultural Credit Corporation.
Mr. Lawrence, do you remember the name of the wholesale grocery that you worked for?
Yeah, Lawrence.
Lawrence.
OK, fine.
Lawrence.
On June 1st, 1933, I became a cashier of the City National Bank.
My first banking experience, I became chief loan officer on the third day of my association with the bank
and continued in that capacity for 27 years, the last 17 of which I was president of the bank.
Since 1960, I have been retired.
And at present, my only business connection is a director of Brown Building and Loan Association.
Thank you, Mr. Lawrence.
Could you tell us perhaps a little about your parents, where they were born and how they came to Bryan?
My father was born 10 miles north of Bryan in the Alexander community in 1873.
After receiving about three and a half years of formal education,
He moved to Brown at about age 10 and lived here the remainder of his life.
My mother was born in Brown across the street from the First United Methodist Church.
As a small child, she moved to another house just south of the courthouse on East 26th at Washington.
And she lived in the shadow of the courthouse practically all the rest of her life.
My father died at age 64, but my mother lived to be 95 years and seven months.
Do you remember when your mother was born?
February 17th, 1874.
You're younger than your father.
Younger than my father.
Your father came here at a young age.
Do you know or did he ever tell you what attracted him to Bryan?
Well, his father had been a farmer and stockman, but he moved to Bryan and set up a lumber company.
Was that named Lawrence also?
It was, but at his death, he left the business to his daughter, who had married him, Mr. Parker.
From then on, it was known as Parker.
I see.
Did you remember your grandfather at all?
No, I didn't.
I never knew either of my grandparents.
I didn't know my paternal grandmother.
I did know them.
My maternal grandmother.
My husband was dead.
I never saw him.
Do you know anything about her, the maternal grandmother?
Yes, she was a native of Bryan, too.
And she was a Miss Hall, the daughter of old Dr. Hall, who was the only doctor in Bryan.
For a good many years.
Well, that's interesting.
I guess perhaps you could tell us just a little bit about your life.
How you saw Brian grow and what you think is significant about it.
Well, in my first recollection, Brown was a town of some 875 people, about half of whom were black.
Brown, the first growth of Brown, real growth, came in 1913 when the federal government created the extension service
and named Texas A&M as headquarters for Texas.
That brought about 75 families into Brazos County.
A&M provided a house for the director.
The other 74 families had to do the best they can, and most of them came into Brown.
And they rented everything available.
But that stimulated a little building, quite a bit of building for a town of that size.
Because by that time, I imagine Brown was a town of maybe 1,800 to 2,000 people.
That was the first real
economic thrust, I suppose you'd call it.

Well, back in those early recollections, who would you say were the controlling families in Bryan, or the socially... besides your own, I'm sure, your father... Well, there were two factions in the town, as you might expect.
One was known as the Parker-Haston faction.
That was...

my father's brother-in-law who operated the lumberyard and also was president of the city national bank and the astons were a big plantation owners razzles bottom but they headquartered in brown and the two of them were those two families were associated together the other family was
headed by old Dr. J.W.
Howell.
Do you remember anything about the Howell family?
Yes, he had three sons, and with them he controlled a bank,

lumberyard cotton compressed and acquired a substantial acreage in the brazos bottom so he was in direct conflict with that parker hasson faction and because he controlled the warehouse and cotton the cotton warehouse and compressed
And those people did not want to patronize him.
They organized another compression lab and set it up near where I was born.
I think you'd mentioned your father had been a rancher.
Was that right?
Or was he in the cotton business?
Grandfather.
Or grandfather, pardon me.
He was a farmer in Maryland, but he also had livestock, more sheep than cattle.
Did your father ever say anything about what kind of crops he grew in those days?
Cotton was the main thing.
It was a cash crop, and corn was to feed his mules and livestock.
That was before the day of the grain salt.
There was no maize or anything like that.
Of course, hay, but... Rolling right along.
Cotton was his cash crop.
How about...
I imagine he had a family.
plot up close to the home where they grew their own vegetables, things of that sort that they wanted to do?
Well, actually, this is a surprise, but those early Texans didn't bother with the garden.
They ate meat and bread and bought little things along from the grocery store, but they didn't need much.
I see.
Lots of them didn't even keep a milk cup.
Both condensed milk.
So I guess the, do you think the diet has changed any?
Your grandfather and your father, what they ate as they grew up as opposed to what you grew up?
I guess you had more and different foods.
Well, when I was a child, we had beefsteak for breakfast.
And we continued that, I guess, until I was 12 or 14 years old.
And then we switched to bacon and eggs, things like that.
But was beefsteak fairly common for most of the families, do you think, at that time?
That was the usual diet.
That's the usual diet.
And they had what they called meat markets.
Lots of the husbands would go down before breakfast, buy meat, stop by the saloon, have a drink or two, and then come home and the wives would cook breakfast.
Well, were there very many saloons here in those days?
There were 13 on Main Street.
13 on Main Street.
They all did pretty good business?
All of them got rich.
All of them got rich.
I noticed some while back, reading a little bit about Brian, that one of the first jails, perhaps it was a county jail, was stuck up into a tree, I think 20 feet or something above it.
Do you ever heard anything about that?
Well, that wasn't an actual jail.
That was what they used to punish obstreperous prisoners.
put them up there and leave them out there in the weather.
I see.
Maybe three or four days, sometimes in the dead of winter, sometimes in the hot summer.
Rain, sleet, whatever.
Usually when they came out of there, they wasn't behaving.
But the first jail I remember was on the
grounds where the president's courthouse is.
I guess that would be the northwest corner.
That was the first jail I remember.
But they had the trees there that they put the obstreperous prisoners in, as I call them.
And of course, at that time, I lived just across the street.
And we used to go over there.
look at them.
Well, you lived pretty close to Miss Carnes, Miss Donut, as they call her.
Yes, we lived as well.
The families knew each other.
Oh, yes.
They were one of the wealthiest families in the county.
He operated a lady's
store, old man, J.W.
Coates.
And then his son took it over.
He was W.J.
Coates.
They were a bunch of initials.
He operated that store a long time.
They also brought quite a bit of acreage in the grass and spotted it.
People of large means, as is evident.
Her husband was a publisher of the Brown Daily Eagle when he died as a young man.
You never remember.
Of course, they left just one block from us.
Those youngsters, you talked a little earlier about playing football around here.
Just neighborhood.
Just neighborhood.
There probably wasn't any organized football, was there, or not much?
They had two teams in.
They had...
Eastern Tigers and Wildcats, they used to play all the time.
They were grown men, what I call them, grown men.
They were 18 to 25, just local.
Of course, they had organized football in A&M as far back as I can remember.
And then...
I guess along about 1910, they started football in high school.
Where was this you played?
And do you remember about when it was where you had this occasion where you were playing safety and moving backwards?
I was in the dirt street between my house where we lived and the courthouse.
And the courthouse.
Yes, it was.
on what is now Texas Avenue between 25th and 26th Street.
You see, we played on that street because the side streets, 25th and 26th, in those days, the grocery stores delivered groceries all over town.
If we tried to play on one of those streets, why, those delivered wagons and interfered with our game.
But they very seldom made that cost.
Of course, there was no traffic because there was no automobile.
At that time, there were five automobiles in the county.
Do you remember hearing anything about the effect of the railroads here when it first came out?
Well, that is what caused...
The growth of Brown, the establishment of Brown in the first place.
You see, Houston and Texas centrally was known then.
Ran from Galveston to Houston.
And then they extended it north to Hampton.
And that was the terminus of the railroad.
Then they extended it to this community of Milliken down here.
But then they had a terrible epidemic of yellow fever down there and practically filled out the town.
So the railroad extended it farther north to Brown and established the town.
At that time,
Boonville out here was the county seat of Brazos County.
But when the railhead came to Brown and began to bring so much business here, you see people came to Brown from as far away as Texarkana, Shreveport, parts of Oklahoma.
We had a big wagon yard here.
They'd come in here and load that freight and then wagon it back to the home.
They also brought the cotton and whatever hides, things like that to Brown, loaded them on the railroad, shipped them to Galveston.
I noticed, of course, the railroad tracks, the spur anyway, this goes right down behind the old stores.
It's pretty handy for the merchants.

Well, that was the reason they located Main Street where it was because the merchants could part on Main and their backs would lead to the railroad and they could unload from the train on a boxcar because they'd
have a spud, and they'd send the boxcars back to the separate stores and load direct to save a double-handle.
And that's the reason they're located on Main Street.
And then behind the end came the International in Great Northern.
It also came from Houston, it came to Brown, and they ran the
down Brown Street.
They went all the way to the oil mill, which was down, I guess, about 14th Street, out of town, past where I was born.
There used to be a cotton oil mill, a cotton seed oil mill down there.
The Howell Fraction owned it, too.
Howell Fraction.
Do you, back in your early recollections, of course your parents, understand, had the, had a wholesale grocery, is that right?
Right here, my father organized that in 1912.
He had a very career, like I told you, he only had about three and a half years of formal education, but he was a
an avid reader, studied, and he was more or less on his own from the time he was about 12 years old.
He delivered papers, organized paper routes, put in a shoeshine business and had a neighbor.
I hadn't run it for me quite as much as a 12-year-old boy.
And he went on to Paris with me.
Then he and Mr. Morris formed a partnership and moved down to Steel Store in the Chrysler's Bottom.
Then around to General Store, including a saloon.
Then they moved to Brown.
set up a retail grocery and a bottling company.
Soft drinks?
Soft drinks.
Sarsaparilla, things like that.
And then my father, of course, they were both under-financed, no money.
My father
Grandpa County Treasurer was re-elected and he moved the office from the courthouse down to his store.
They had that retail grocery and of course the money from that office and the tide of the mobile especially through the panic of 1907.
And then in 1912 the owner of the building
wanted to bring his nephew over here from England and set him up in the grocery business, so he refused to extend John M. Lawrence and Company's lease.
So Mr. Moring went across the street and became manager of Parker-Aston Hardware Company.
which was a newly organized business and my father started operating it and he continued in that business until his death in 1938.
I understand that when the courthouse was built that there's quite a bit of land speculation around there they thought the merchants would all try to build around the
courthouse like we see in so many cities?
Well, a few of them did, but because of the situation of the railroad, they never could overcome that.
Most of the stores preferred to be down on the railroad for convenience and lower overhead as well.
You don't recall whoever put their money into land speculation around the courthouse, whether they were upset about it or... No, I don't remember much about it.
In fact, there never was much, but the telephone company was there just across.
They're still in that same location.
Of course, they're spread out, but that's a big office.
That same thing.
It was there when I was a boy.
And then on that block, there was a general merchandise, largely a feed store, which later failed.
There was a law office.
The lady had a millinery store.
And there was a tombstone factory or sale
How about your education?
Can you tell us a little bit about where you went to school and how long?
I went to the public school here in Brown.
I started on what was known as Westside.
It's a boys' school now.
It was a brand-new building.
And I went there two years, and then I transferred over to the east side, where they had the entire school from first grade to year 11.
And then at that time, you did not have to have a high school diploma to enter A&M.
And I had enough credits to get in, so I entered A&M in 1915, incidentally at the age of 15.
That's quite an accomplishment.
And I went to A&M three years, and now my husband's a major.
They only had two schools at that time, agriculture and engineering.
And then World War I broke out, and in 1918 they lowered the draft age to 18 and also reduced the age required to hold a commission to 18, so I entered the training camp.
was commissioned as second lieutenant.
I got out of the service on December the 22nd.
And then January 1st, I enrolled at the University of Texas in business administration.
And I went there two years, but I never did graduate anyway.
high school, A&M, and university.
Well, that's something to go that long in a university and not having graduated from high school.
That's quite an achievement there in itself.
Well, I didn't have to have an diploma in A&M.
I built up enough credits to enter the university, but I lost so many in the transfer that I wasn't anything like them.
Let me move the tape over to the other side.
I think we've come close to the end.
So we don't get interrupted.
